{{Infobox organization | name = Sustainable South Bronx | named_after = [[South Bronx]] | image = SSBx Logo transparent.png | image_size = 150px | alt = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | map = <!-- map image --> | map_alt = | map_caption = | map2 = <!-- second map image, if required --> | map2_size = | map2_alt = | map2_caption = | abbreviation = SSBx | motto = | established = {{Start date and age|2001}} | founder = [[Majora Carter]] | founding_location = [[Hunts Point, Bronx]] | type = [[Economic development corporation]] | status = [[501(c)(3)]] | purpose = [[Environmental organization]] | headquarters = 1647 Macombs Rd. Bronx, NY 10453 USA | location = | coords = <!-- location's {{coord}}s --> | region = <!-- or: | region_served = --> <!--Any particular region or regions associated with or served by the organization--> | services = | membership = <!-- Usually the number of members --> | membership_year = <!-- Year to which membership number/data apply --> | leader_title = Executive Director | leader_name = Michael Brotchner | leader_title2 = | leader_name2 = | board_of_directors = | key_people = | main_organ = <!-- or: | publication = --> <!--Organization's principal body (assembly, committee, board, etc) or publication--> | parent_organization = The HOPE Program | subsidiaries = SmartRoofs, LLC. | affiliations = | budget = $1,439,509 | budget_year = 2014 | staff = <!-- Numbers and/or types of staff --> | staff_year = <!-- Year to which staff numbers/data apply --> | volunteers = <!-- Numbers and/or types of volunteers --> | volunteers_year = <!-- Year to which volunteer numbers/data apply --> | slogan = <!-- in quotemarks / inverted commas --> | website = {{url|www.ssbx.org }} | remarks = | footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|title=Charity Navigator - Rating for Sustainable South Bronx|url=https://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=14728|website=Charity Navigator|accessdate=18 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> }}
'''Sustainable South Bronx''' (SSBx) is a non-profit workforce development and [[environmental justice]] solutions organization in [[New York City]]'s [[South Bronx]] neighborhood, founded by [[Majora Carter]] in 2001.<ref name=Rockwell>Cynthia E. Rockwell, "Breaking the Grip of Poverty", ''Wesleyan'' ([[Wesleyan University]] alumni magazine), Issue IV 2006, 33–37.</ref> Today, it is a division of the Brooklyn-based workforce development organization,The HOPE Program.<ref name="coolroofs">{{cite web|title=NYC CoolRoofs - NYC Business|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/nycbusiness/article/nyc-coolroofs|website=www1.nyc.gov|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref>
The organization spearheaded the creation of [[Hunts Point Riverside Park]], the first piece of the projected [[South Bronx Greenway]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Daniel|title=Sustainable South Bronx wins EPA award|url=https://nypost.com/2010/04/30/sustainable-south-bronx-wins-epa-award/|website=New York Post|accessdate=18 December 2017|date=30 April 2010}}</ref> This organization also pioneered a "[[green roof]]" project in the South Bronx with its own for-profit installation company SmartRoofs, LLC, and started a "green-collar" job training program called Bronx Environmental Stewardship Program (B.E.S.T.) which prepares urban residents in areas such as ecological restoration, [[hazardous waste]] cleanup, [[green roof]] installation and maintenance, urban forestry, and landscaping; the program has a 90% placement rate after four years of operation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Green|first1=Emily|title=Self-gentrification: A South Bronx lesson for Portland {{!}} Street Roots|url=http://news.streetroots.org/2016/12/12/self-gentrification-south-bronx-lesson-portland|website=news.streetroots.org|publisher=Street Roots News|accessdate=18 December 2017|date=12 Dec 2016}}</ref> They are also proposing a Bronx Eco-Industrial Complex as an alternative use for a piece of land where the city government currently is planning to construct a [[prison]], and are engaged in developing "a collection of businesses in which the waste and byproducts of one business are the raw materials for another one."<ref name=Rockwell />
In 2005, SSBx built the "Cool and Greenroof Demonstration Project" above their offices in the historic American Banknote Building&nbsp;— the first such roof in the City of New York. In 2007, SSBx launched the for-profit SmartRoofs, LLC green roof installation business.
Today, SSBx still runs a robust 12 week green jobs training program (formerly called the Bronx Environmental Stewardship Training (BEST), now called Sustainable South Bronx. Training topics range from landscaping, energy auditing, green infrastructure, OSHA and BPI certifications and more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehopeprogram.org/how-it-works/|title=How It Works|website=The HOPE Program|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref> This program aims to provide economic empowerment to the community through training, employment and career services, while contributing to the environmental sustainability of New York City. SSBx also runs two transitional employment programs, which provide participants with on the job training, valuable experience, and a fair wage for their work. [https://www1.nyc.gov/nycbusiness/article/nyc-coolroofs NYC °CoolRoofs] hires New Yorkers to coat NYC rooftops with a reflective material, easing buildings' energy consumption and mitigating the [[Urban heat island|urban heat island effect]]. [http://www.intervine.nyc/ Intervine], SSBx's social enterprise, trains and employs low-income community members to create and maintain green infrastructure.
