{{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:Japanese words and phrases]]}} [[File:Art House Project03s3872.jpg|thumb|Traditional houses in [[Naoshima, Kagawa]] clad with ''yakisugi'' panels]] [[File:Setouchi Yakisugi.jpg|thumb|Close-up view of charred ''yakisugi'' board]] '''''Yakisugi''''' ([[wikt:焼|焼]][[wikt:杉|杉]]) is a traditional [[Japanese aesthetics|Japanese]] method of [[wood preservation]]. ''Yaki'' means to heat with fire, and ''sugi'' is [[Cryptomeria japonica|cypress]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/19/t-magazine/shou-sugi-ban.html The Latest Design Trend: Black and Burned Wood] AMANDA FORTINI, [[New York Times]], September 19, 2017</ref> It is also referred to in the West as ''shō sugi ban'' (焼杉板),<ref>[http://shousugiban.co.uk/ shousugiban.co.uk]</ref> which uses the same ''[[kanji]]'' characters but [[Kunyomi|a different pronunciation]]. The ''ban'' character means "[[plank (wood)|plank]]".
By slightly [[charring]] the surface of the wood without combusting the whole piece, the wood becomes water-proof through the carbonisation and is thus more durable.<ref>[http://charredwood.com/traditional-japanese-burnt-wood-shou-sugi-ban-yakisugi/ charredwood.com]</ref> It also protects against insects.
Contemporary architect [[Terunobu Fujimori]] works with ''yakisugi''.<ref>[https://www.dezeen.com/2009/03/11/yakisugi-house-by-terunobu-fujimori/ Yakisugi House by Terunobu Fujimori] Megan Wilton, [[Dezeen]], 11 March 2009, Photograph: Edmund Sumner </ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/lifestyle/interiors/6104653/Interiors-A-Japanese-charred-timber-house-inspired-by-a-cave-dwelling.html Interiors: A Japanese charred-timber house inspired by a cave dwelling] Yuki Sumner, [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]], 28 August 2009</ref>
